To handle binary data such as file downloads in an `XMLHttpRequest`, you should set the `responseType` property to `"blob"`. This allows the response to be treated as a `Blob` object, which can then be used to handle binary data appropriately.

Here is an example of how you might set this up:

```javascript
var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open('GET', 'your-file-url', true);
xhr.responseType = 'blob';

xhr.onload = function() {
  if (xhr.status === 200) {
    // The response is a Blob
    var blob = xhr.response;
    // You can now use the blob, for example, to create a URL for downloading
    var url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
    var a = document.createElement('a');
    a.href = url;
    a.download = 'filename'; // Set the filename for the download
    document.body.appendChild(a);
    a.click();
    // Clean up
    URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
    document.body.removeChild(a);
  }
};

xhr.send();
```

Setting the `responseType` to `"blob"` ensures that the response is handled as binary data, making it suitable for file downloads and other binary data operations.

In LaTeX, when using the `titlesec` package, you can define the style of a custom sectioning level such as `subsubsubsection` using the `\titleformat` command. Here is how you can define a custom sectioning level:

1. First, you need to define the new sectioning level using `\newcommand` or `\newcounter`.

2. Then, use the `\titleformat` command to specify the style.

3. Optionally, use `\titlespacing` to adjust the spacing.

Here is an example of how you might define and style a `subsubsubsection`:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{titlesec}

% Define a new counter for subsubsubsection
\newcounter{subsubsubsection}[subsubsection]

% Define the command for subsubsubsection
\newcommand{\subsubsubsection}[1]{%
  \refstepcounter{subsubsubsection}%
  \paragraph*{\thesubsubsection.\arabic{subsubsubsection}~#1}%
}

% Define the format for subsubsubsection
\titleformat{\subsubsubsection}[runin]
  {\normalfont\normalsize\bfseries}{\thesubsubsection.\arabic{subsubsubsection}}{1em}{}

% Define the spacing for subsubsubsection
\titlespacing*{\subsubsubsection}{0pt}{1.5ex plus 1ex minus .2ex}{1em}

\begin{document}

\section{Section}
\subsection{Subsection}
\subsubsection{Subsubsection}
\subsubsubsection{Subsubsubsection}
Some text under the subsubsubsection.

\end{document}
```

In this example:
- `\newcounter{subsubsubsection}[subsubsection]` creates a new counter for `subsubsubsection`, resetting every `subsubsection`.
- `\titleformat{\subsubsubsection}[runin]` defines the format of the `subsubsubsection` using the `runin` style, which makes the heading run into the text.
- `\titlespacing*{\subsubsubsection}{0pt}{1.5ex plus 1ex minus .2ex}{1em}` adjusts the spacing before and after the heading.

This setup allows you to create a custom sectioning level similar to `subsubsection` but one level deeper. Adjust the format and spacing as needed to fit your document style.

